# Differential Timely Dataflow Execution

## Description

Timely dataflow provides the execution substrate for differential dataflow. It models computation as a directed graph of operators connected by typed edges, with a progress-tracking protocol that determines when all messages at a given logical time have been delivered. This enables operators to know when their input at a specific time is complete, allowing them to produce correct outputs and compact their internal state.

**Core concepts:**
- **Timestamp**: Logical time associated with every message (data, time, diff)
- **Progress tracking**: Protocol to determine when all data at time T has arrived
- **Frontier**: The set of times that might still produce messages
- **Capability**: Token that allows an operator to send messages at time T
- **Notification**: Signal that no more messages will arrive at time T

**Key characteristics:**
- **Streaming with correctness**: Progress tracking enables exactly-once semantics
- **Nested timestamps**: Support for iterative computations (loops)
- **Partially ordered time**: Enables multi-dimensional progress
- **Distributed**: Progress protocol works across network boundaries
- **Low latency**: Sub-millisecond end-to-end for simple pipelines

**Trade-offs:**
- Progress tracking overhead per message batch
- Timestamp management complexity for nested scopes
- Coordination cost increases with graph complexity
- Memory for buffering messages until frontier advances

## Relational Algebra

```
Timely dataflow execution model:

Collection = multiset of (data, time, diff) triples
  time: logical timestamp (partially ordered)
  diff: +1 (insert) or -1 (retract)

Operator contract:
  - Receives: batches of (data, time, diff)
  - Produces: batches of (data, time', diff')
  - Holds: capabilities for times it may still emit
  - Receives: notifications when frontier advances past time T

Progress tracking:
  frontier(operator) = { times T : operator may still produce at T }

  An operator at time T is "complete" when:
    forall upstream operators U:
      frontier(U) does not contain any time <= T

  When complete(T):
    operator can compact state for times <= T
    downstream can process all data at time T
```

## Implementation

```rust
/// Timely dataflow worker executing a dataflow graph
pub struct TimelyWorker {
    graph: DataflowGraph,
    progress_tracker: ProgressTracker,
    pending_messages: Vec<MessageBatch>,
}

/// Progress tracking frontier
pub struct Frontier {
    /// Set of active times (antichain: no time dominates another)
    times: Vec<Timestamp>,
}

impl Frontier {
    /// Check if a time is still possible
    pub fn less_equal(&self, time: &Timestamp) -> bool {
        self.times.iter().any(|t| t <= time)
    }

    /// Advance frontier: remove old times, add new
    pub fn advance(&mut self, old: &Timestamp, new: &Timestamp) {
        self.times.retain(|t| t != old);
        if !self.times.iter().any(|t| t <= new) {
            self.times.push(new.clone());
        }
    }
}

/// A differential dataflow operator
pub trait DifferentialOperator {
    /// Process a batch of changes at given times
    fn process_batch(
        &mut self,
        input: &[(Data, Timestamp, Diff)],
        output: &mut Vec<(Data, Timestamp, Diff)>,
    );

    /// Called when frontier advances past a time
    fn notify(&mut self, time: &Timestamp) {
        // Compact internal state for completed times
        self.compact_state(time);
    }

    /// Current capability (times this operator may still emit)
    fn frontier(&self) -> &Frontier;
}

/// Timely progress tracking protocol
pub struct ProgressTracker {
    /// Per-operator frontier information
    operator_frontiers: Vec<Frontier>,
    /// Pending progress updates
    pending_updates: Vec<ProgressUpdate>,
}

impl ProgressTracker {
    /// Process progress updates and determine completions
    pub fn advance(&mut self) -> Vec<Notification> {
        let mut notifications = Vec::new();

        for (op_id, frontier) in self.operator_frontiers.iter().enumerate() {
            // Check if any upstream frontiers advanced
            let upstream_complete = self.all_upstream_past(
                op_id, frontier,
            );

            if upstream_complete {
                // All upstream operators have advanced past these times
                for time in frontier.completed_times() {
                    notifications.push(Notification {
                        operator: op_id,
                        time: time.clone(),
                    });
                }
            }
        }

        notifications
    }

    fn all_upstream_past(
        &self,
        op_id: usize,
        frontier: &Frontier,
    ) -> bool {
        // Check all operators that feed into op_id
        for upstream in self.upstream_operators(op_id) {
            let up_frontier = &self.operator_frontiers[upstream];
            for time in &frontier.times {
                if up_frontier.less_equal(time) {
                    return false; // Upstream may still send at this time
                }
            }
        }
        true
    }
}

/// Example: Filter operator in differential timely dataflow
pub struct DifferentialFilter {
    predicate: Expr,
    frontier: Frontier,
}

impl DifferentialOperator for DifferentialFilter {
    fn process_batch(
        &mut self,
        input: &[(Data, Timestamp, Diff)],
        output: &mut Vec<(Data, Timestamp, Diff)>,
    ) {
        for (data, time, diff) in input {
            if eval_predicate(&self.predicate, data) {
                output.push((data.clone(), time.clone(), *diff));
            }
        }
    }

    fn frontier(&self) -> &Frontier {
        &self.frontier
    }
}

/// Cost model for timely dataflow execution
pub fn timely_dataflow_cost(
    changes_per_second: f64,
    num_operators: usize,
    graph_depth: usize,
) -> f64 {
    // Per-change processing
    let process_cost = changes_per_second * num_operators as f64
        * 0.000001; // ~1 us per operator per change

    // Progress tracking overhead
    let progress_cost = changes_per_second * graph_depth as f64
        * 0.0000001; // ~100 ns per frontier update

    // Latency: end-to-end for one change
    let latency_ms = graph_depth as f64 * 0.1; // ~0.1ms per operator hop

    process_cost + progress_cost
}
```

## Cost Model

**Per-Change Processing:**
- Operator processing: ~0.1-10 us per change per operator
- Message serialization (if distributed): ~1-5 us
- State lookup: ~0.1-1 us (hash table probe)
- Total per-change latency: `graph_depth x operator_cost`

**Progress Tracking:**
- Frontier update: ~100 ns per operator per batch
- Notification delivery: ~50 ns per notification
- Overhead ratio: typically < 5% of total processing

**State Management:**
- Per-operator state: proportional to active data at operator
- State compaction: triggered by frontier advancement
- Memory: sum of all operator states

**Latency Breakdown (typical):**
- Input ingestion: 0.1 ms
- Per-operator hop: 0.1-0.5 ms
- Progress tracking round: 0.05 ms
- 5-operator pipeline: ~1-3 ms end-to-end

## Test Cases

```sql
-- Test 1: Simple filter pipeline (low latency)
CREATE MATERIALIZED VIEW active_users AS
SELECT * FROM users WHERE active = true;
-- INSERT INTO users VALUES (1, 'Alice', true);
-- Expected: ~0.5ms latency from insert to view update
-- Progress: single timestamp, simple advancement

-- Test 2: Multi-operator pipeline
CREATE MATERIALIZED VIEW revenue_by_region AS
SELECT region, SUM(amount) FROM orders
WHERE date > NOW() - INTERVAL '1 day'
GROUP BY region;
-- Pipeline: Filter -> Aggregate
-- Expected: ~2ms latency per order insert
-- State: aggregate HT compacted when day boundary passes

-- Test 3: Iterative computation (nested timestamps)
-- Transitive closure (recursive query)
-- Timely uses nested timestamp (outer_time, iteration)
-- Progress tracks both outer and inner time dimensions

-- Test 4: High-throughput ingestion
-- 100K events/second through 5-operator pipeline
-- Expected: batch progress updates every 10ms
-- Throughput: limited by slowest operator
```

